1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
They brought me in here to this place

2
00:00:02,209 --> 00:00:05,626
The judge sat on a chair here, with a table in front of him

3
00:00:05,876 --> 00:00:07,209
And I was in this spot

4
00:00:08,125 --> 00:00:10,334
Interviewer: Were you sitting or standing?
Witness: No, I was standing

5
00:00:10,959 --> 00:00:12,542
I was standing, and he was sitting

6
00:00:13,626 --> 00:00:14,709
He started asking me questions

7
00:00:15,709 --> 00:00:17,918
What is your name? Are you from this area?

8
00:00:19,125 --> 00:00:22,542
And what do you know about the Christians here?

9
00:00:22,542 --> 00:00:25,500
I told him, They are peaceful, simple people

10
00:00:26,209 --> 00:00:28,459
They are our neighbors, and we have spent our lives together

11
00:00:30,375 --> 00:00:33,375
He asked me, Do they like you or not?

12
00:00:33,918 --> 00:00:37,709
I told him, They like us; they are good people, and we have lived with them for years

13
00:00:37,709 --> 00:00:41,667
We sleep at one another’s houses, we share food, and things like that

14
00:00:43,918 --> 00:00:45,918
Then he asked me about medicine

15
00:00:47,083 --> 00:00:50,292
Where do you get the medicine from? And why do you distribute it?

16
00:00:50,334 --> 00:00:51,751
And to whom do you distribute it? Do you sell it?

17
00:00:52,250 --> 00:00:53,876
I told him, I do not sell it

18
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:56,334
It is all labeled, “Distributed for free”

19
00:00:56,417 --> 00:00:59,751
If they are inhalers for asthma treatment, it says on them “Distributed for free”

20
00:01:00,667 --> 00:01:02,250
And also Tenormin tablets for blood pressure

21
00:01:02,959 --> 00:01:05,000
And Isordil for the heart, that is what I had

22
00:01:05,667 --> 00:01:06,834
I distribute it to people for free

23
00:01:06,876 --> 00:01:10,167
Because some people are poor and cannot afford to buy it

24
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:11,667
I give it to them for free

25
00:01:13,209 --> 00:01:16,792
He said, We asked about you, and your reputation is good

26
00:01:18,125 --> 00:01:21,000
But we will interrogate you as well, because we have many questions for you

27
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:29,334
And when it was time for the noon prayer, they took me upstairs

28
00:01:32,792 --> 00:01:34,167
To the archbishopric

29
00:01:34,459 --> 00:01:36,626
Interviewer: In the other building?
Witness: Yes, the one in back

30
00:01:37,751 --> 00:01:40,083
We went to the archbishopric and prayed there

31
00:01:40,792 --> 00:01:43,125
There is a place designated for prayer

32
00:01:43,584 --> 00:01:45,667
It was time for the noon prayer, so we prayed

33
00:01:46,417 --> 00:01:48,542
We finished, then he interrogated me

34
00:01:48,959 --> 00:01:50,375
Interviewer: What did he interrogate you about there?

35
00:01:51,375 --> 00:01:52,709
He asked me about the Christians

36
00:01:52,792 --> 00:01:56,959
He said, Since you used to enter these churches

37
00:01:56,959 --> 00:01:58,792
What do you know about what is inside the churches?

38
00:01:59,417 --> 00:02:02,834
I told him, I do not know everything about the inside of the church

39
00:02:02,918 --> 00:02:06,167
This was a burial place reserved for the priests

40
00:02:07,250 --> 00:02:08,792
In the Church of Mary

41
00:02:09,167 --> 00:02:12,250
When the priests died, they were buried there

42
00:02:12,292 --> 00:02:13,292
That is what I know

43
00:02:14,375 --> 00:02:16,959
I told him, There was a library

44
00:02:17,209 --> 00:02:19,626
That is what I had known before

45
00:02:22,375 --> 00:02:23,417
So he nodded his head

46
00:02:25,417 --> 00:02:29,959
He said, We will transfer you to the rooms upstairs

47
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:31,751
Then we will bring you back later

48
00:02:32,459 --> 00:02:36,250
Interviewer: During his interrogation of you in this place or in the archbishopric

49
00:02:36,292 --> 00:02:40,542
Did he say harsh words or insult you—no offense, or did he beat you?

50
00:02:40,584 --> 00:02:44,834
Yes, they spoke to me with a tone of intimidation and terrorizing

51
00:02:45,167 --> 00:02:48,000
Interviewer: How so? Tell me the words and describe the situation?

52
00:02:48,292 --> 00:02:50,125
Tell us, or we know what we will do to you

53
00:02:51,375 --> 00:02:52,417
Interviewer: Tell us?

54
00:02:52,459 --> 00:02:55,542
Yes, tell us, or we know what to do with you

55
00:02:56,918 --> 00:02:59,709
As if he was threatening me, a threat

56
00:03:00,542 --> 00:03:02,834
And when he threatens me, fear strikes me more

57
00:03:03,959 --> 00:03:05,876
That is what was happening to me

58
00:03:05,918 --> 00:03:07,083
Interviewer: And did he sense your fear?

59
00:03:07,167 --> 00:03:08,709
Yes, he sensed my fear—I was afraid

60
00:03:09,167 --> 00:03:10,334
Because they cannot be trusted

61
00:03:11,626 --> 00:03:14,417
Because their work is beheading, killing, and flogging

62
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:18,334
And I have a family, and my mind was preoccupied with my children and my wife

63
00:03:18,417 --> 00:03:20,292
Because they did not know where I was

64
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,459
Interviewer: During the interrogation with
you in this place or in the archbishopric

65
00:03:26,834 --> 00:03:32,042
Did he make a threat like, Speak, or I will
extend your prison term, or I will kill you?

66
00:03:32,042 --> 00:03:34,375
Yes, that is exactly what he said

67
00:03:35,209 --> 00:03:39,125
If you do not speak, we will keep you with us,
and no one will know where you are except God

68
00:03:40,209 --> 00:03:42,626
He kept repeating this sentence

69
00:03:44,042 --> 00:03:45,250
Interviewer: And what did you say?

70
00:03:45,792 --> 00:03:48,500
I told him, Ask me, and I will tell you what I know

71
00:03:49,792 --> 00:03:52,792
I told him, What else shall I tell you; should I tell you that these are walls

72
00:03:54,334 --> 00:03:56,125
You asked me about such-and-such a priest

73
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,500
About Father Ishaq, may God have mercy on him

74
00:04:00,250 --> 00:04:04,667
He was our neighbor, and he did his duty in the church

75
00:04:04,709 --> 00:04:06,209
He was my friend, and I used to sit with him

76
00:04:08,125 --> 00:04:10,042
And he asked me about the priests

77
00:04:11,375 --> 00:04:13,417
About the priest of one church, and the priest of another church

78
00:04:13,459 --> 00:04:17,209
I told him what I knew, and I did not tell him what I did not know

79
00:04:17,459 --> 00:04:19,334
Interviewer: Why did he ask you specifically about the priests?

80
00:04:19,334 --> 00:04:21,667
Because he knew that I was from this area

81
00:04:22,709 --> 00:04:24,542
They asked about me and learnt that I was from this area

82
00:04:24,542 --> 00:04:25,876
And we have been living here for 50 years

83
00:04:27,375 --> 00:04:28,959
Interviewer: Regarding this place

84
00:04:30,751 --> 00:04:37,042
I want you to describe this place to me when you arrived as a prisoner

85
00:04:37,250 --> 00:04:39,959
What was in it, and what furniture was there?

86
00:04:40,042 --> 00:04:43,709
Was there one of their banners hanging? Tell me about these details

87
00:04:43,709 --> 00:04:46,334
Yes, there was their black flag

88
00:04:47,375 --> 00:04:49,542
It had written on it, “There is no God but God, and Muhammad is the Messenger of God”

89
00:04:51,167 --> 00:04:54,542
And there was a white curtain

90
00:04:56,459 --> 00:04:59,000
And there was a place for prayer where they prayed

91
00:05:00,042 --> 00:05:01,292
Interviewer: Did you pray there?

92
00:05:01,334 --> 00:05:04,250
I prayed two <i>rakaas</i> here, then I went and prayed the noon prayer there

93
00:05:05,125 --> 00:05:07,459
Interviewer: Do you mean you prayed the <i>sunnah</i> prayer?
Witness: Yes, the <i>sunnah</i>

94
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,500
Interviewer: And the obligatory prayer—where?
Witness: The obligatory prayer was there

95
00:05:09,542 --> 00:05:13,292
Interviewer: What does this place you are in now remind you of?

96
00:05:13,709 --> 00:05:17,334
And is there a particular smell present until now?

97
00:05:17,417 --> 00:05:20,667
When you entered, did you smell it and did it
remind you of the incident that happened to you?

98
00:05:20,709 --> 00:05:23,250
And did these details remind you of that situation you were in?

99
00:05:23,459 --> 00:05:27,667
Do you feel today the same fear you felt back then?

100
00:05:27,876 --> 00:05:31,834
So describe to me your feeling now since you entered the same place

101
00:05:31,918 --> 00:05:35,626
I am afraid to this moment although I am here with you

102
00:05:38,042 --> 00:05:40,000
The fear is still inside me

103
00:05:40,375 --> 00:05:42,626
Interviewer: So you were afraid of the interrogation

104
00:05:42,709 --> 00:05:46,000
And of the unknown, meaning they might kill you

105
00:05:46,125 --> 00:05:48,250
Why are you afraid now since you entered this place?

106
00:05:48,584 --> 00:05:52,250
Because when they used to speak to me

107
00:05:53,209 --> 00:05:54,584
Their words were harsh and frightening

108
00:05:55,125 --> 00:05:56,626
And I am still afraid

109
00:05:57,584 --> 00:05:59,542
Even though you are filming me

110
00:05:59,834 --> 00:06:01,751
Because I suffered a psychological problem

111
00:06:02,500 --> 00:06:04,083
A very severe psychological problem

112
00:06:05,292 --> 00:06:09,959
And I am still taking psychiatric medications

113
00:06:10,834 --> 00:06:16,334
And now that we entered here, I will need medicine to calm my nerves

114
00:06:16,792 --> 00:06:20,834
Interviewer: So since you entered the place and remembered the incident

115
00:06:20,834 --> 00:06:22,167
Witness: Yes, I am still afraid

116
00:06:22,209 --> 00:06:25,375
Interviewer: So the feeling of fear came back to you again?
Witness: Yes

117
00:06:26,042 --> 00:06:33,626
Interviewer: Do you mean you now feel emotions and remember painful memories?

118
00:06:34,250 --> 00:06:35,250
Yes, it is so

119
00:06:36,167 --> 00:06:39,918
Interviewer: Did we exhaust you psychologically by standing here?

120
00:06:39,918 --> 00:06:41,709
Yes, I am tired

121
00:06:42,834 --> 00:06:43,834
I have been worn out psychologically

122
00:06:45,209 --> 00:06:50,375
Interviewer: Do you want us to talk outside or stay here? What do you think?

123
00:06:50,417 --> 00:06:51,542
Outside is better

124
00:06:52,584 --> 00:06:56,751
Interviewer: Has being in this place exhausted
you to the point that you want to leave?

125
00:06:56,876 --> 00:06:57,876
Yes, I have become tired

126
00:07:00,125 --> 00:07:01,876
Interviewer: Is the place that frightening?

127
00:07:02,876 --> 00:07:05,584
Yes, I remember painful events that happened to me

128
00:07:06,751 --> 00:07:10,167
Interviewer: Did anything happen here in front of you
besides the interrogation, like beatings, for example?

129
00:07:10,209 --> 00:07:13,751
They were talking among themselves that
they had taken so-and-so and killed him

130
00:07:13,834 --> 00:07:15,584
And so-and-so they took to another place, and so on

131
00:07:16,042 --> 00:07:17,626
And we brought so-and-so from that place

132
00:07:17,626 --> 00:07:20,209
They mentioned names when they spoke with each other

133
00:07:20,250 --> 00:07:21,250
Interviewer: During the interrogation?

134
00:07:21,250 --> 00:07:23,709
Yes, I would hear them when they talked among themselves

135
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:29,459
When they spoke like that, I felt that what
happened to others would happen to me

136
00:07:29,959 --> 00:07:32,834
Interviewer: Are the colors of these
walls the same, or did anything change?

137
00:07:32,876 --> 00:07:33,876
Yes, they are the same

138
00:07:34,375 --> 00:07:35,667
Interviewer: Was there nothing else in here?

139
00:07:35,959 --> 00:07:39,209
No, there was not—only their flags

140
00:07:39,876 --> 00:07:42,167
And there was a white curtain

141
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:47,209
And two black flags of ISIS, one there and the other there

142
00:07:47,959 --> 00:07:52,125
Interviewer: When you entered this place

143
00:07:54,292 --> 00:07:57,751
And you said that you now recall the fear and terror you felt

144
00:07:57,876 --> 00:08:01,792
And you had a reaction from that while you were talking with us

145
00:08:04,500 --> 00:08:06,375
Is there a particular smell you still remember?

146
00:08:06,459 --> 00:08:10,250
Interviewer: Or do you now smell a scent that was here?
Witness: Yes

147
00:08:10,334 --> 00:08:12,042
Interviewer: What is this smell?

148
00:08:12,959 --> 00:08:15,751
The smell of fear and terror

149
00:08:16,918 --> 00:08:20,584
Because I know that their work is with blood, beheading, and killing
